---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";

// The Offer, Decoded. A page family. Each page pairs one advertised carrier
// promotion with the binding terms that govern it, quoted verbatim from the
// carrier's own published pages, with the capture date and, where we have one,
// an archive link. Facts only. Any read on what the facts add up to belongs on
// a commentary page, not here.

const pages = [
  {
    href: "/decoded/att-iphone-on-us",
    carrier: "AT&T",
    title: "iPhone on us, up to $1,100 off",
    blurb:
      "The AT&T trade-in promotion, decoded from AT&T's own published trade-in pages.",
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="The Offer, Decoded"
  description="The offer as advertised, then the binding terms that govern it, quoted verbatim from the carrier's own published pages, with capture dates and archive links."
>
  <div class="wrap prose" data-pagefind-body>
    <h1>The Offer, Decoded</h1>

    <p>
      Carrier device promotions are advertised in a few large words and governed
      by many small ones. This page family sets the two side by side. First the
      offer as it is advertised. Then the binding terms that govern it, quoted
      word for word from the carrier's own published pages, with the date we
      captured each page and, where one exists, a link to an archived copy.
    </p>

    <p>
      We do not paraphrase inside quotation marks. We do not tell you what the
      terms mean for you. Plain headers group the quotes by the question a buyer
      would ask. Where the published terms do not answer a question, we say so
      and name the question rather than fill it in.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you are comfortable with these conditions, the offer may work for you.
      The point is knowing them before you sign.
    </p>

    <h2>Decodes</h2>
    <ul class="card-grid">
      {
        pages.map((p) => (
          <li class="card">
            <h3>{p.carrier}: {p.title}</h3>
            <p>{p.blurb}</p>
            <a class="btn" href={p.href}>
              Read the decode
            </a>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>

    <h2>How to read these pages</h2>
    <p>
      Every quote carries the name of the source page we captured and the date
      we captured it. When a quote looks incomplete or unusual, it is reproduced
      as the captured page stored it. For how the terms archive is built, see the
      <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> page.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
